BSE PATHOGENESIS
================
[1]
Date: Sat, 16 Mar 1996 15:25:00 GMT
Via: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@rz.uni-karlsruhe.de>
From: Tommasso Picardo <tpicardo@cix.compulink.co.uk>
Subject: BSE and prions
BSE, cause and affect:
It is reported that the BSE agent can not be found in various organs of
affected animals. If the theory of the prion protein is correct then
infected meat taken orally has prions present. Is the prion small enough
to pass through the stomach walls? Which part of the stomach does it
pass through and do different conditions affect it i.e. pH2, pH9? Once
through the stomach walls does it pass throughout the body in the blood
leading into the brain, and once in the brain, does the prion pass into
the brain cells or, does it get trapped outside the cells where by
certain reactions releases toxins being responsible for the appearance of
lesions? If the prion is present in the blood why does it not show as
being present in other organs or; is it attacked by the immune system or,
is it not found as it is not looked for or, is it to hard to find without
physical evidence i.e. lesions, or? In experiments it is quoted that
mice are fed intravenously through the spine with BSE infected material
but is this not a different route to that of animals that were fed
ruminant material i.e. therefore can the results be accepted?

Tommasso Picardo

tpicardo@cix.compulink.co.uk
